title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.2.1: STRENGTHENED MULTISECTORAL APPROACH IN NUTRITION

description.narrative: By the end of 2025, actors at central, regional, and local levels have strengthened managerial capacities for greaterefficiency and accountability in implementing the multisectoral, multi-stakeholder approach and regulation in nutrition., which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Evaluation, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition In Early Childhood (Covid), Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2025, children (girls and boys), adolescents, and pregnant and lactating women, especially the most vulnerable, have access to an adequate diet and adopt optimal feeding and care practices through adequate services.

title.narrative: By the end of 2025, actors at central, regional, and local levels have strengthened managerial capacities for greaterefficiencyand accountability in implementing the multisectoral, multi-stakeholder approach and regulation in nutrition.

description.narrative: The CO continued to strengthen its leadership in nutrition during 2021 by shifting the nutrition programme from a health-sector approach to a multi-system approach to accelerate stunting reduction, in line with key results for children (KRC2), and expanding accountability for child nutrition to other sectors and systems. For this purpose, the CO relied on partnership platforms such as the: UN SUN movement network, technical and financial partners’ group on nutrition and multi-sectoral information platform for nutrition. The CO supported evidence-based programming through a final review of the national multisectoral plan 20162020 and evaluation of the acute malnutrition management programme.; | Status:Met | As-of Date:17/01/2022
